# 2. Different Ethereum Networks

---

## A) Mainnet

### Definition

The Mainnet is the original Ethereum blockchain where real transactions occur.

### Features

- Uses real ETH
- Fully functional network
- Network ID = 1
- Open to everyone

---

## B) Beacon Chain

### Definition

The Beacon Chain manages Ethereum's Proof of Stake (PoS) consensus.

### Features

- Launched in December 2020
- Coordinates validators
- Later merged with Ethereum Mainnet

---

## C) Test Networks (Testnets)

### Definition

Testnets are Ethereum networks used for testing Smart Contracts and DApps without spending real ETH.

### Test ETH

Test ETH is obtained through **Faucets**.

---

## Sepolia

### Features

- Replaced Ropsten
- Uses Proof of Stake
- Preferred for Smart Contract and DApp development
- Network ID = 1115511

---

## Goerli (Deprecated)

### Features

- First cross-client testnet
- Uses Proof of Stake
- Network ID = 5

---

## Holesky

### Features

- Successor of Goerli
- Used for staking and infrastructure testing

---

# 3. Ethereum Clients

## Definition

An Ethereum Client is software that performs the functions of an Ethereum node.

---

# Post-Merge Architecture

```
Ethereum Client

↓

Execution Client (Eth1)

+

Consensus Client (Eth2)
```

---

## Execution Client (Eth1)

### Functions

- Processes transactions
- Executes transactions inside EVM
- Stores blockchain data

### Examples

- Geth (Go)
- Hyperledger Besu (Java)
- Erigon (Go)
- Nethermind (C#/.NET)

---

## Consensus Client (Eth2)

### Functions

- Runs on Beacon Chain
- Handles Proof of Stake consensus
- Uses data from Execution Client

### Examples

- Prysm (Go)
- Teku (Java)
- Lighthouse (Rust)
- Nimbus (Nim)

---

# Before Merge vs After Merge

| Before Merge | After Merge |
|--------------|-------------|
| Only Execution Client | Execution + Consensus Client |
| Proof of Work (PoW) | Proof of Stake (PoS) |

