# Important Definitions

## Ethereum Node

A computer participating in the Ethereum blockchain network.

---

## Full Node

Stores the complete blockchain and validates transactions.

---

## Light Node

Stores only block headers and fetches data when needed.

---

## Archive Node

Stores the complete blockchain along with all historical states.

---

## Mainnet

The official Ethereum blockchain where real ETH transactions occur.

---

## Beacon Chain

Blockchain responsible for Ethereum's Proof of Stake consensus.

---

## Testnet

A testing network used for developing Smart Contracts and DApps without real ETH.

---

## Execution Client

Processes transactions and executes Smart Contracts.

---

## Consensus Client

Handles Proof of Stake consensus and validator coordination.

---

## Remix VM

Built-in virtual blockchain provided by Remix IDE.

---

## Hardhat Node

Local Ethereum blockchain used for Smart Contract testing.

---

# Key Takeaways

- Ethereum supports Full, Light, and Archive Nodes.
- Mainnet is used for real transactions, while Testnets are used for development.
- After The Merge, Ethereum requires both Execution and Consensus Clients.
- Remix VM and Hardhat Node are widely used for Smart Contract development and testing.
- Sepolia is the preferred Ethereum test network for modern DApp development.

---

# Summary

The Ethereum Network is maintained by different types of nodes and clients that work together to process transactions and maintain consensus. Developers use Testnets such as Sepolia and simulation tools like Remix VM and Hardhat Node to build and test Smart Contracts before deploying them on the Ethereum Mainnet.